Based on the retrieved evidence, complex fractionated atrial electrograms (CFAE) are primarily associated with regions of dyssynchronous activation and abnormal conduction patterns, commonly found near areas of high dominant frequency and reentry circuits in atrial fibrillation. Multiple sources confirm that CFAE arises from disrupted conduction due to tissue heterogeneity and reentrant dynamics, which are fundamental features shared across various supraventricular arrhythmias—including sinus rhythm fractionation—which likewise stems from dyssynchronized activation. Since both phenomena originate from similar underlying pathophysiologic principles involving disorganized electrical propagation in a heterogeneous myocardium, the presence of fractionated electrograms reflects comparable electrophysiological instability irrespective of the current rhythm state. Therefore, I agree with option A—the relationship exists because both CFAE and sinus rhythm fractionation stem from common mechanisms of dyssynchronous activation and abnormal conduction.
